relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Researchers are advised to consult the Eddie Sauter Papers (MSS 64) and the Benny Goodman Papers (MSS 53), both held by the Gilmore Music Library.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Sauter-Finegan Orchestra was formed in 1952 by Eddie Sauter (1914-1981) and Bill Finegan (1917-2008). Sauter and Finegan were each prominent arrangers for big bands led by artists such as Glenn Miller, Benny Goodman and Tommy Dorsey. Finegan had studied with Stefan Wolpe and Darius Milhaud, and Sauter studied music at Columbia and Juilliard. Both were clearly influenced by classical music, and their orchestra included non-traditional big band instruments like the recorder, piccolo, English horn, and tympani.

Sauter and Finegan wrote arrangements of big band standards, but they also ventured into folk and classical music, e.g., "Doodletown Fifers", their version of "Yankee Doodle". In 1953, Sauter and Finegan put together a touring orchestra, but their venture did not prove successful. They disbanded the Orchestra in 1957, although they reunited to record an album in 1959. The Orchestra was featured in a 1960 Buick commercial, perhaps a precursor to Sauter and Finegan's involvement in writing commercial jingles for television.

In the 1980s, Bill Finegan revived the Sauter-Finegan Orchestra name for concerts in New York City at venues such as Town Hall and 92nd Street Y. The orchestra was called, "Studio Orchestra" as it was made up of highly-skilled studio musicians in New York City at the time. The Studio Orchestra was led by Harvey Estrin, one of the original members of the Sauter-Finegan Orchestra.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: MSS 140, The Sauter-Finegan Orchestra Papers in the Gilmore Music Library of Yale University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: At this time, the Papers include a portion of the Sauter-Finegan Orchestra arrangements. The parts and the scores have been organized into separate series because they were received separately. Not all of the parts have a corresponding score at this time.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Original parts for the following titles have been removed for preservation reasons: "Hearts are Young," "Moonlight on the Ganges," "Nina Never Knew," "Azure-Te," "April in Paris," and "Midnight Sleighride." Photocopies of these parts remain in the collection.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Papers are divided into three series: 1. Parts, 2. Scores, and 3. Conductor's Scores.

controlaccess.subject: Big band music -- Scores and parts

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The parts are arranged in alphabetical order by title.

scopecontent.p: Condensed versions of full scores, with instrumental cues. Some are labeled "Booth" rather than "Conductor".

scopecontent.p: A few pages of playlists and notes from Sauter-Finegan Orchestra concert series in the late 1970s and 1980s, New York City. Contained in a folder labeled "Conductor - Studio Orchestra".
